{{TransH}}
''Naruto'' was published in Shueisha's magazine, ''Weekly Shōnen Jump'' from September 21, 1999 to November 10, 2014.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Valdez |first=Nick |date=2019-09-21 |title=Naruto Fans Can't Believe the Series Turns 20 Today |work=Comicbook.com |url=https://comicbook.com/anime/news/naruto-20th-anniversary-celebration-anime-fans-twitter/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20210219211806/https://comicbook.com/anime/news/naruto-20th-anniversary-celebration-anime-fans-twitter/ |archive-date=2021-02-19 |language=en-US }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Brown |first=Urian |date=2014-11-10 |title=Viz Blog / This Week's Issue! - Nov 10, 2014 |url=https://www.viz.com/blog/posts/this-week-s-issue-2380 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20210219212701/https://www.viz.com/blog/posts/this-week-s-issue-2380 |archive-date=2021-02-19 |publisher=[[Viz_Media|Viz Media]] |language=en-US }}</ref> The manga was also published in ''tankōbon'' (book) form in Japan and other countries, releasing 72 volumes—27 for Part I, and the rest for Part II. The first 238 chapters are Part I and constitute the first section of the ''Naruto'' storyline. Chapters 239 to 244 include a ''[[gaiden|gaiden]]'' (side-story) focusing on Kakashi Hatake's background. The remaining chapters (245 to 700) belong to Part II, which continues the story after a {{frac|2|1|2}}-year gap in the internal timeline.<ref name="NarutoShueishaVolume58">{{cite web|url=http://books.shueisha.co.jp/CGI/search/syousai_put.cgi?isbn_cd=978-4-08-873828-4|title=Naruto 28|publisher=[[Shueisha|Shueisha]]|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170620054610/http://books.shueisha.co.jp/CGI/search/syousai_put.cgi?isbn_cd=978-4-08-873828-4|archive-date=2017-06-20|url-status=live}}</ref>  The first ''tankōbon'' was released on March 3, 2000.<ref name="NarutoJPNVolume1">{{cite web|url=http://books.shueisha.co.jp/CGI/search/syousai_put.cgi?isbn_cd=4-08-872840-8&mode=1 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160222085957/http://books.shueisha.co.jp/CGI/search/syousai_put.cgi?isbn_cd=4-08-872840-8&mode=1 |archive-date=2016-02-22 |title=Naruto 1 |language=ja |publisher=[[Shueisha|Shueisha]]|url-status=dead }}</ref> Shueisha have also released several [[Films_comic|ani-manga]] ''tankōbon'', each based on one of the ''Naruto'' movies,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/s?url=search-alias=stripbooks&field-keywords=Naruto+Ani-Manga |title=Naruto Ani-Manga: Books |publisher=Amazon|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170620034109/https://www.amazon.com/s?url=search-alias%3Dstripbooks&field-keywords=Naruto%20Ani-Manga |archive-date=2017-06-20 |url-status=live }}</ref> and has released the series in Japanese for cell-phone download on their website ''Shueisha Manga Capsule''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mangacapsule.jp/pc/ |title=NARUTO —ナルト— |publisher=[[Shueisha|Shueisha]] |trans-title=Naruto |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090101124901/http://mangacapsule.jp/pc/ |archive-date=2009-01-01|url-status=dead }}</ref> A miniseries titled {{nihongo foot|''[[Naruto:_The_Seventh_Hokage_and_the_Scarlet_Spring|Naruto: The Seventh Hokage and the Scarlet Spring]]''|{{ruby-ja|NARUTO|ナルト}}外伝・七代目火影と緋色の花つ月|Naruto Gaiden: Nanadaime Hokage to Akairo no Hanatsuzuki|group=lower-alpha}}, centered on the main characters' children, began serialization in the Japanese and English editions of ''Weekly Shōnen Jump'' on April 27, 2015, and ended after ten chapters on July 6, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-03-26/naruto-spinoff-manga-mini-series-to-begin-on-april-27/.86389 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161225025537/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-03-26/naruto-spinoff-manga-mini-series-to-begin-on-april-27/.86389 |archive-date=2016-12-25 |title=Naruto Spinoff Manga Mini-Series to Begin on April 27 |work=[[Anime_News_Network|Anime News Network]] |date=2015-03-26|url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-04-20/naruto-sequel-spinoff-manga-to-run-in-viz-shonen-jump/.87324 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160505071021/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-04-20/naruto-sequel-spinoff-manga-to-run-in-viz-shonen-jump/.87324 |archive-date=2016-05-05 |title=Naruto Sequel Spinoff Manga to Run in Viz's Shonen Jump |work=[[Anime_News_Network|Anime News Network]] |date=2015-04-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

''Naruto'' was [[scanlation|scanlated]] (translated by fans) and available online before a licensed version was released in North America;<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2006/09/07/culture/fans-lift-j-culture-over-language-barrier/#.T_Oij_VTi59 |title=Fans lift J-culture over language barrier {{!}} The Japan Times |last=Macias |first=Patrick |date=2006-09-07 |work=[[The_Japan_Times|The Japan Times]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611065114/http://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2006/09/07/culture/fans-lift-j-culture-over-language-barrier/#.WUlAVWgrK01 |archive-date=2016-06-11 |url-status=live |author-link=Patrick Macias}}</ref>  the rights were acquired by Viz Media, who began serializing ''Naruto'' in their anthology comic magazine ''[[Shonen_Jump_(magazine)|Shonen Jump]]'', starting with the January 2003 issue.<ref name="ANNNarutoManga">{{cite news|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2002-08-01/shonen-jump-press-release |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161225210629/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2002-08-01/shonen-jump-press-release |archive-date=2016-12-25 |title=Shonen Jump Press Release |work=[[Anime_News_Network|Anime News Network]] |date=2002-08-01|url-status=dead }}</ref>  The schedule was accelerated at the end of 2007 to catch up with the Japanese version,<ref name="PublisherWeeklyNarutoNation">{{cite web|url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/1-legacy/24-comic-book-reviews/article/12945-viz-speeds-up-naruto-releases.html|title=Viz Speeds Up Naruto Releases|date=2007-05-01|publisher=PWxyz, LLC|work=[[Publishers_Weekly|Publishers Weekly]]|author=Alverson, Brigid|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130201035824/http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/1-legacy/24-comic-book-reviews/article/12945-viz-speeds-up-naruto-releases.html|archive-date=2013-02-01}}</ref> and again in early 2009, with 11 volumes (from 34 to 44) appearing in three months, after which it returned to a quarterly schedule.<ref name="Campaign2">{{Cite web |url=http://www.viz.com/news/newsroom/?id=169 |title=A New Generation, A New Destiny |date=2008-11-17 |publisher=[[Viz_Media|Viz Media]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081216075136/http://www.viz.com/news/newsroom/?id=169 |archive-date=2008-12-16 |url-status=dead}}</ref> All 27 volumes of Part I were released in a boxed set on November 13, 2007.<ref name="VolumeSetAmazon">{{cite book|title=Fall 2007 Naruto Box Set, Volumes 1–27 (Naruto) |df=mdy-all |isbn = 978-1-4215-1980-7|last = Media|first = Viz|date=2007 }}</ref> On May 3, 2011, Viz started selling the manga in an omnibus format with each book containing three volumes.<ref>{{cite book |title=Naruto: 3-in-1 Edition, Vol. 1 (Uzumaki Naruto / The Worst Client / Dreams) |df=mdy-all |isbn=978-1-4215-3989-8 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/naruto3in1volume0001kish |year=2011 |last=Kishimoto |first=Masashi }}</ref>

The franchise has been licensed in 90 countries, and the manga serialized in 35 countries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.txhd.co.jp/en/ir/library/business/pdf/index_2008.pdf |title=TV Tokyo – Annual Reports 2008 |publisher=[[TV_Tokyo|TV Tokyo]] |page=12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120716182530/http://www.tv-tokyo.co.jp/contents/ir/eng/report/pdf/ar2008/ar2008.pdf |archive-date=2012-07-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name="Million">{{cite news|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2014-11-08/naruto-manga-has-200-million-in-print-worldwide/.80771|title=Naruto Manga Has 200 Million in Print Worldwide|date=2014-11-09|work=[[Anime_News_Network|Anime News Network]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160910230815/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2014-11-08/naruto-manga-has-200-million-in-print-worldwide/.80771|archive-date=2016-09-10|url-status=dead}}</ref>[[Madman_Entertainment|Madman Entertainment]] began publishing ''Naruto'' volumes in Australia and New Zealand in March 2008 after reaching a distribution deal with Viz Media.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2008-02-23 |title=Viz Media Teams With Madman Entertainment on Manga |url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/press-release/2008-02-23/viz-media-teams-with-madman-entertainment-on-manga |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150531053323/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/press-release/2008-02-23/viz-media-teams-with-madman-entertainment-on-manga |archive-date=2015-05-31 |publisher=[[Anime_News_Network|Anime News Network]]}}</ref> [[Carlsen_Verlag|Carlsen Comics]] has licensed the series, through its regional divisions, and released the series in German and Danish.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.carlsen.de/serie/naruto/17266 |title=Naruto |publisher=[[Carlsen_Verlag|Carlsen Comics]] |language=de |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160507180120/https://www.carlsen.de/serie/naruto/17266 |archive-date=2016-05-07 |url-status=dead}}</ref> The series is also lice